---
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import config from "@/config";
---

<Layout
  title={`Prompt-to-Ontology | ${config.site.title}`}
  description="A public experiment on transforming messy product requirements, prompts, and business concepts into structured ontology assets for enterprise AI systems."
>
  <Header />

  <Main pageTitle="Prompt-to-Ontology" class="app-prose">
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      A public experiment on transforming messy product requirements, prompts,
      and business concepts into structured ontology assets for enterprise AI
      systems.
    </p>

    <div class="border-border mt-4 flex flex-wrap gap-2">
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        Knowledge Graphs
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        Neo4j
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        NetworkX
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        ReAct Agent
      </span>
      <span class="rounded-full border px-3 py-1 text-xs font-medium">
        LLM Pair Programming
      </span>
    </div>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">The Problem</h2>
    <p>
      Enterprise AI systems often fail because the underlying data model doesn't
      match how the business actually works. Traditional data models show tables
      and columns, but miss the relationships, constraints, and operations that
      define real business logic. When you build an AI agent on top of a bad
      data model, the agent reasons about a fictional version of your business.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Why Ontology Matters</h2>
    <p>
      An ontology captures not just entities and attributes, but relationships,
      constraints, and the actions those entities enable. For enterprise AI, this
      is the difference between a chatbot that gives generic answers and an agent
      that can actually operate on your business context.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">What I Built</h2>
    <p>
      Prompt-to-Ontology takes raw CSV data and transforms it into an
      interactive knowledge graph. An LLM infers the ontology schema — entities,
      relationships, constraints — then writes it into a Neo4j graph database. A
      ReAct agent sits on top, ready to query the graph and suggest business
      actions with human-in-the-loop approval.
    </p>
    <p>
      The architecture separates three concerns: <strong>Neo4j</strong> as the data
      source, <strong>NetworkX</strong> as the compute engine, and the <strong
        >LLM</strong
      > as the reasoning layer. Three decoupled systems that can be independently
      replaced.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Key Insight</h2>
    <p>
      Fact tables are nodes, not edges. An order isn't a relationship between a
      customer and a product — it's an independent entity connected to both via
      separate edges. Get this wrong and your entire graph topology collapses.
    </p>
    <p>
      A knowledge graph without action buttons is just a pretty picture. Every
      node type has context-sensitive operations calculated from its current
      state — a low inventory node lights up a "Create Purchase Order" button.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Vibe Coding Approach</h2>
    <p>
      No sprint planning. No stand-ups. No traditional software engineers. Just
      one product manager defining product intent, architecture boundaries, and
      design constraints — and one LLM handling code generation, debugging, and
      iteration.
    </p>
    <p>
      The most valuable output isn't code. It's the cognitive framework for
      understanding ontology-driven systems: the difference between data models,
      schemas, and ontologies; the distinction between "viewing a graph" and
      "operating a business through a graph."
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Status</h2>
    <p>Public repository, actively being extended.</p>

    <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a
        href="https://github.com/wenhaoyu-bryan/prompt-to-ontology"
        class="bg-accent text-accent-foreground inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium transition-opacity hover:opacity-90"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >
        View on GitHub
      </a>
      <a
        href="/posts/building-ontology-os"
        class="border-border text-foreground inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md border px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium transition-colors hover:bg-accent/10"
      >
        Read the Blog Post
      </a>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
